The court also supported the remaining parts of the law on 2700 pages and further ruled that the statutory requirement for health care, which requires states to expand the possibility of obtaining sickness insurance, otherwise there is a risk of the loss of all financing of sickness insurance from federal sources, is not coercive and contrary to the Constitution.
