Is the European elite ready to trade with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise to bring businesses together and define what changes in relation to the EU want to see by British business and job-creating companies.
To this end, we have commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey in which we asked leading British businessmen about their views on Britain, trade and the EU.
YouGov asked 1 000 leading entrepreneurs representing British businesses of various sizes and from different sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will be a surprise to many.
We have found that the vast majority of businesses are now trying to export outside Europe and focus on countries that are modernizing and growing while EU countries are stagnating.
They want to see the government prefer new trade ties with countries such as China, India and Brazil, rather than getting bogged down in a long and strenuous process of reforming mysterious European institutions.
When we asked their views on specific policy areas – from monopoly regulations to product laws – most entrepreneurs expressed the view that the control of these key competencies should be returned to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market and entrepreneurs said that the costs of Brussels’ regulations now outweigh the benefits of being part of the European business area – even 40 percent of large enterprises, traditionally the most pro-European companies, agreed.
Finally, our survey by business leaders revealed the most eloquent knowledge, namely that a clear majority wants Britain to strive for a change in the treaty and the relationship with the EU, which should be based on trade, not politics.
The findings with which businesses of different sizes and core business groups have identified is that the business sector is pushing for a “meaningful change” that will bring back to Britain.
There is a lot at stake – reaching a treaty change and a better deal for Britain can mean a gain of up to 16% in a referendum in the EU referendum.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate: this survey shows that British trade supports his plan to amend the terms of Britain's EU membership.
It also shows that the business sector expects this amendment to be a significant shift from the current balance of forces back towards Britain.
A better deal for Britain is possible, and given the way the eurozone is embarking on a journey to a narrower economic and fiscal union, and increasingly necessary.
Jobs and growth in Britain must be a priority, and as the results of our survey show, for business, this means a re-focus on trade and a fundamental change in the regulatory approach of Brussels.
