Frontier Airlines prepares to charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge an amount of up to $100 on its flights for the storage of hand luggage on board.
Frontier Airlines plans to introduce a fee of up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 per coffee or soda, although in their announcement on Wednesday they said passengers would be able to keep the whole can.
The new hand luggage fee covers luggage in the upper storage compartment, so small luggage under the seat will continue to be free of charge.
Frontier says it will charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 if passengers with payment will wait until they arrive at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the hundred-dollar fee is intended to encourage passengers to take care of the payment in advance.
"We don't want to collect this fee," she said.
Airlines began charging for the first and second bags in 2008.
Passengers tried to avoid these fees and stuffed in the hand luggage hidden in the storage compartment as much as they could, so that space was often lacking in this space.
Fees are one of the ways to teach passengers to take fewer things on board.
O'Malley said the point of this new fee really isn't to get more money.
The point is that Frontier’s most loyal customers have made it quite clear that finding a place in the upper storage space is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who purchase tickets on the company's website will not pay.
This means that one passenger in the queue at the Frontier gate can bring luggage for which they will not pay anything, while the other passenger queues for the same luggage pays $100.
O'Malley said the website and check-in procedures will be modified to ensure that passengers learn about the fee before they arrive at the gate.
Frontier's new fee for hand luggage will not be valid until the summer, but the date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage fees and other fees, but airlines love them.
They claim that handling luggage costs money, and passengers who require this service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street perceive an additional baggage fee as a sign that airlines are trying to raise enough money to cover the cost of air traffic after years of losses.
Most of them did not reach for hand luggage charges.
Spirit Airlines was the first to charge for hand luggage three years ago, and another low-car car company, Allegiant Air, later followed.
The only company that also has such fees is Hungary's Wizz Air, says air transport advisor Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors additional charges.
In his December 2011 report, he estimated that Spirit’s hand luggage fee would deliver $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently flew with Spirit and wondered what he saw at the gate when passengers met Spirit's unusual fee for hand luggage.
"Arriving a plane was the smoothest I've ever seen in my aviation career," he said.
I was expecting to see a gnashing of teeth and quarrels at the gate.
The plane was full, he said, "and the onset took place in an instant."
Frontier, also, following the model of Spirit, will apply the fees for coffee, tea, soda and juice.
Frontier said passengers who get lemonade or juice can keep the whole can and the coffee will be replenished free of charge.
Water will continue to be served for free.
In 2008, US Airways briefly attempted to introduce beverage charges, but after complaints from passengers, it withdrew from which seven months later, and no other major airline mimited it.
Frontier's latest move to charge for hand luggage if passengers do not purchase a flight directly from this airline is its last effort to direct customers directly to their website.
Airlines pay online travel retailers such as Orbitz, from $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to lead passengers to purchase directly from them, instead of doing it through online travel agencies.
However, Frontier has gone the furthest in this area.
In September, she began giving only half a million to customers who had purchased through an online travel agency as part of a loyalty program.
On Wednesday, she cropped a reward for a mile-fly to 25 percent of the trip.
So the journey with Frontier 1000 miles long purchased through an online travel agency means a reward of 250 miles.
The company also allows customers to choose their seat in advance only if they make the purchase directly through the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in its hometown Denver, but its business is starting to shrink and losing money.
According to financial results presented on Wednesday, corporate partner Republic Airways Holdings sales fell by 9 percent, and transport capacity decreased by almost 13 percent in the first quarter
By selling this airline, Republic is also trying to solve the financial problems of Frontier.
