He himself became a vascular surgeon at a central hospital in Yaounde.
And he founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, whose members visit rural areas over the weekend, where they provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he has helped almost 32 000 people with his group of volunteers.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people are packed into the vans, attaching medical supplies to the roofs and traveling through harsh terrain to villages that need help.
They are not always accompanied by happiness.
More than once, vehicles have to push through the river and mud.
But when they arrive, they get a welcome as real heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the community can offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really the reason to celebrate, and Bwelle – with its broad smile and unbridled energy – is very willing to engage in local merriment.
The next day, the team begins to treat hundreds of patients.
"We have 500 patients on every quest," says Bwelle.
They come to the village from a radius of 60 kilometers, on foot.
During each of these weekends, doctors provide various medical assistance.
Many are treated with malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasitic diseases and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can get crutches or donated glasses or a free birth certificate – a document that requires a school, but which many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team makes simple surgeries under local anaesism.
Surgeries are usually done in the school building, at the town hall or at home; after surgery, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery site to make room for another patient.
With the help of a light from the generator, the operating room and the sanitary equipment of Bwelle and its volunteers work until the early hours of the morning.
It's exhausting, but village musicians usually help the team not to lose motivation.
"To stay awake and continue to work, they're playing drums all night," says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team will head back into the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group – consisting of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – performed 700 free operations last year and realizes that their help can mean a lot to local residents.
One man said he would be able to work again after the hernia surgery.
"That will change our future for our family," the man said.
In addition to organizing these weekend clinics and the work of a surgeon at Bwelle Hospital, he also works for private medical clinics around Yaounde at night.
He says that this second thesis finances about 60% of his non-profit activities; the rest are covered by private contributions.
“I’m not sure when she’s actually sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia for the second year and volunteers for Bwelle’s group.
He's always in a hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can do these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who came from the United States or Europe to join Bwelle on his mission, this is a great practice they wouldn't get at home.
"We washed our hands thoroughly for Dr. Bwellem and removed blood stains or held his tools," O'Malley says.
You will never experience this as a second-year medical student in America.
Students volunteers usually pay their way to Cameroon themselves and often arrive with donated medical supplies.
But as soon as they arrive in Yaounde, food, transportation and study is provided by Bwelle.
"Without a doubt he's a hero," O'Malley says.
This organization gives his life, and its desire to help the inhabitants of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwelle, the constant harness is not a burden.
To help others live happier, to fulfill the promise he made to his father is something that brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," Bwelle says.
