Since Scotland is not in Schengen now, the supply of continued mismatch would be a cheap concession for Brussels in return for anything they really want from the Scots.
So it's a pretty weak story.
And so old that it became an excavator. I heard the journalistic duck that “independence means passport controls” at least 40 years ago.
Yet there is an interesting idea in this bearded story.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to obey Europe?
Why exchange a London-based dom for the Brussels one, especially now?
This is a real European story: the big post-war plan to unite Europe has finally failed.
Due to the euro crisis, the so-called Europe Project is officially dead.
Across Europe, the influence of the parties are initiated by the opposition to the EU or the abolition of the euro as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany – founded this year – came from nowhere and already in the September federal elections captured almost five million votes, essentially “sweaking” the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats).
On home soil, there has always been a dislike of the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has become a decisive moment.
The economy dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, together with a straitjacket threaded to the national economies through clinging to the common currency, have led many people to believe that the Europe project had gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments manage a high budget deficit – that was only true in the case of Greece.
Rather, it is a system of euros that blocks its members at exchange rates advantageous for German exporters – and German politicians want to keep that.
Without the possibility of devaluing the domestic currency, southern Europe has a disadvantage in the domestic production sector compared to Germany.
The only help is to cut income and public spending – which is what Germany encourages.
Behind the current budget and currency problems is a deeper cause of European malaise performance.
As a result of the “green” energy policy supported by Brussels – a code to support French and German firms at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much as electricity and four times more for gasoline than is in the United States.
This is a paralyzing disadvantage in the area of costs, as we have already seen in the case of Grangemouth.
Even all the wages freeze in the world would not avert the sealing of the European petrochemical industry with cheap shale oil from the US.
The result is a smoldering rebellative, especially in France, once enthusiastic supporters of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool to keep Germany at bay and allow Paris to stand up to the level of Washington in the world.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a card of political legitimacy and has established its own economic policy in Europe and left the worn French economy to its fate.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right wing, the anti-European National Front, has just won a major extra election and pushed the ruling Socialists third.
The front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – an early warning to British Labour that they cannot conclude that the cleavage of the right will automatically positively affect the left.
How does Le Pen handle her newfound popularity among the white working class?
Next year’s European elections would like to make an anti-European bloc operating against the common currency across the European Parliament.
If the anti-European parties do well in this election, which is likely, such a bloc may dominate for the first time in the history of the European Parliament.
It occurs to me that in the foreseeable future, the growing anti-European feeling and the attitude against the common currency will come together and the euro will be destroyed.
The EU will not disappear, but will be transformed rather into something looser in the sense of the “Europes (Souvenient) of the Nations,” which was preferred by General de Gaulle.
Germany and several of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project and adhere to the United States.
But Washington's increased interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left to the Atlantic cold.
And where will Scotland be?
We can choose to be an area of (in principle) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – this includes the possibility of announcing Berlin and Brussels, when they should leave us alone.
I suppose Scotland would do well in Europe's relaxed arrangement, provided it retaining its own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should take the example of Norway and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – surprisingly – the most successful political movement that does not promote austerity measures in Europe, which was won by a large majority in 2011 thanks to the opposition stance on the cuts planned (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the following coalition of Conservatives and Liberal Democrats.
It would be ridiculous if Scotland now voted for independence just to take austerity measures dictated by Berlin and Brussels.
