Earlier research has shown that joyful dogs wagging their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs wave their tail mostly to the left.
But now scientists say that other dogs can record these subtle differences in the movement of the tail and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortipara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trent, said: "It is well known to humans that the left and right sides of the brain have different links to stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions."
We tried to observe the same thing in other species.
He added that, as is the case with humans, the right side of the brain is responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa, and that these two hemispheres play a different role in emotions.
In an effort to get more information about how dogs respond to asymmetrical stings of the tail of other dogs, researchers monitored animals that watched films about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side, and other times on top of that.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We have projected dogs films about dogs - whether in the natural version or in the form of a silhouette - to get rid of any confusing stimuli, and we were also able to adjust the movement of the tail and represent it more to the right or left."
When the animals saw an otherwise insignificant dog moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of a dog wagging its tail), they remained completely calm.
But when she recorded the rotation of the tail mostly to the left (again from the point of view of a dog wagging a tail), their heart rate increased and the animals looked uncertain.
Professor Vallortipara said he didn't think dogs would consciously communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they have to and that they do not have to look out for.
He said: "If you meet dogs several times and the movement of their tail in one direction is repeatedly associated with rather friendly behavior, and the movement to the right breeds less friendly behavior, you will respond based on this experience."
Researchers say the findings can help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand the emotions of their animals.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a university veterinarian at the University of Bristol, said it was not the first study to examine whether the left and right side were important to dogs.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads off as they observe an aggressive dog, and to the right, looking at a cheerful dog.
And in another expert treatise from Victoria University in Canada, he said: “The dog robot was more likely to become acquainted with a dog robot when they were wagging their tail to the left than to the right, when they were rather insecure – exactly compared to the Italian study.”
According to him, the difference may be due to the fact that dogs in these various studies did not interpret animals in movies or dog robots completely as dogs.
He explained that studies on how dogs respond to real dogs could help.
“Even though there are strong evidence in the case of many different mammals that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
