Six out of ten companies are preparing for the new Civil Code
Six out of ten companies are intensively preparing for the imministeration of the new Civil Code and the Business Corporations Act on 1 January 2014.
Only eight percent of the company's representatives surveyed said they had not addressed the issues related to both key codes in their company at all.
This is according to a survey by Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal, which surveyed the opinions of 108 Czech companies.
In the context of the approaching effective date of both key codes, only at the last minute are a number of managers starting to realize the significant impact on the business of their companies.
In our opinion, the biggest changes in private law in the last 50 years will affect all citizens and companies in the Czech Republic.
Because of the lavish of politicians, the business sector has long lived in uncertainty whether revolutionary changes will eventually occur or not.
"Now, however, they only have a few weeks left to switch to the new right for their companies without complications," Jan Spáčil, Ambruz & Dark Deloitte's partner, commented on the results.
Of the 61 percent, intensively engaged in the new laws, 26 percent said their firms had already taken all the necessary measures to be prepared in time.
In addition, 35 percent of the companies in this number are going to take the necessary measures in the near future.
One in five companies has not yet dealt with reconducting, yet they have a concrete idea of how to prepare for them.
A total of 11 percent do not have an opinion and cannot assess the issue.
Only eight percent of companies admit that they have not yet addressed the issues related to recodification.
The most important legal issue related to the new Civil Code is for the largest number of companies surveyed, the conclusion of new contracts (21 percent), followed by the solution of business conditions (16 percent) and changes in the cadastre of real estate and in liability for damage (after ten percent).
Contracts will take place one of the most important innovations of the entire recodification, i.e. the unification of the modification of contracts only under the new Civil Code.
The current parallel regulation in the Civil and Commercial Code will cease to exist, as a result of which the contractual law should become clearer for citizens and entrepreneurs.
"In the case of entrepreneurs, the new regulation will offer many novelties with an emphasis on greater freedom of relations," said Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal attorney Lukáš Poddaný.
In connection with the Business Corporations Act, almost a quarter of companies consider the issue of increasing the liability of statutory bodies to be the most important topic.
Furthermore, the topics related to changes in the convocation and progress of the general meeting (15 percent) and the representation of the company (14 percent) follow.
The new legislation means tightening the obligations and possible impacts for statutory bodies, especially in a situation where a company is threatened with or is incapable of bankruptcy.
"In practice, this means that if the members of the boards of directors and the executives of the companies do not act with the care of a proper manager and do not avert the impending bankruptcy of the company, they may lose the benefit gained for the performance of the office only in the last two years," Spáčil added.
