New Nicocin Disease Can Take away Smoking Enjoyment
Scientists have developed a nicotine vaccine that can take away the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
The only dose of the vaccine was able to protect the mouse from nicotine addiction for life.
Before the human trials, it is necessary to carry out additional tests that will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of the Weill Cornell Medical School in New York says the first signs are good.
"We firmly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help millions of smokers who have tried to quit and exhaust all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine addiction is so strong to overcome all current approaches," said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry genetic information to create anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begin to form a smooth stream of these antibodies.
Antibodies persecute all nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they get into the brain, preventing the smoker from getting nicotine hit.
During the tests of the vaccinated mice, to which nicotine was additionally delivered, they continued their normal activities.
But mice that weren't vaccinated "cayed," the researchers said, a sign that nicotine got into their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translation Medicineal.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The injections had to be given as often as to maintain sufficient levels of antibodies, so they proved to be expensive and impractical.
The cost of new vaccines should be much lower because they convert liver cells into factories to produce antibodies.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines are completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they feel like trying a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
However, it would be much more likely to be used by smokers to stop.
"They'll know if they start smoking again, they won't enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that's going to help them get rid of this habit," he said.
British scientists have said the results were interesting, but they point out that further research is needed.
