Nathaniel P. Morris has been studying medicine at Harvard for the second year.
I'm reading a sad book these days.
I thought about this book that would encourage me during the sloppy days of my second year at medical school and restore me a bit of hope.
It's called "The Audacity to Win" and it's about memories of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish patient testimonials in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and the speeches took your breath away.
The election ended in overwhelming predominance, and television news forced us to reflect on the historical value of the moment.
My classmates wept with joy, and my parents were hiding the newspaper they had found.
A young team of visionaries headed to the White House, and the nation was ready for change.
During his inauguration in 2008, Obama had the support of 82 percent.
And I'm closing the book here.
Going to the present is a harsh awakening, like waking up from a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic days – they seem to be distant memories, a sad reminder of the missed opportunities.
In the years after I dropped my first ballot paper, there were actually changes.
It was definitely nothing I imagined.
I recognize that Obama has achieved a number of great and diverse achievements – from the law on affordable care through the withdrawal of our troops from Iraq and the end of politics “not to ask for anything, not to say anything” after the killing of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I am convinced that party obstructions have reversed so much effort to move our nation forward: among other things, it is an immigration reform, the possibility of public choosing health care and closing the base in Guantnám.
But after many situations where I defended the Obama administration in front of colleagues and friends, I have reached an absolute limit in terms of explanations that they can provide.
I found myself in a place of political hopelessness.
Obstructions of Republicans cannot explain the approval of eavesdropping on foreign leaders or airstrikes of drones that kill innocent children overseas.
It cannot be explained by the fact that the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans, nor that it is persecuting those who uncover the wrong actions of the government.
They cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without a proper trial or for restricting public contributions and spending during presidential campaigns.
They cannot justify the findings of a report that says that the White House's efforts to silence the media are "the most aggressive ... from the Nixon administration."
And most recently, they cannot excuse the inability to create a simple website more than 3 years after signing the Affordable Care Act.
