Should the mother be frightened when her daughter begins to grow breasts and hair on the shaming at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatricians this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new standard.
"I spent a lot of time trying to assure my parents that it's usually not a sign of rapid development towards full puberty," Kaplowitz said.
Visible signs of development, such as breast growth, hair on the sham and armpits and body odors, appear in girls earlier.
In the last forty years, however, there has been only a small shift at the age when the first menstruation occurs.
In the United States, it is now an average age of 12.5 years, compared to the age of 12.75 in 1970.
“When the breasts start to develop, at least two to three years pass before the first menstruation occurs,” said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of “Early puberty in girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.”
The most reliable test of how puberty will continue is time.
There is a debate about what activates the actual beginning of puberty, but if breast growth is accompanied by growth spurt before the age of 8, the girl is considered "prematurely advanced."
In most cases, the process slows down or stops – which can be carefully monitored by pediatricians.
Faster growth may be a reason for the endocrinologist to conduct tests to eliminate serious problems such as a tumor or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature aging of bones, which can eventually lead to a cessation of growth and dwarf in adulthood.
Recommendations on drugs and hormonal treatment are dependent on the age of the child, the speed of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocialic aspects are also important.
When it comes to taking medication, Kaplowitz is cautious, but recognizes that "suppressing puberty can alleviate problems with the girl's behavior and her feelings that she differs from her peers."
What is understandable is another big problem: Parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
"They're worried that he can get pregnant or how he's going to handle hygiene," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter began to have her period at the age of 10.
