There are many well-known theories about the causes of premature puberty.
However, there is no coherent set of evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual message in the media are to blame.
Boys – like girls – reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz promotes the assumption that the most serious reason is the epidemic of obesity.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study on girls aged 6 to 9, which combines body fat with the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-Americans and Hispanics tend to reach puberty before their white counterparts.
The explanations are different.
From a global perspective, the patterns of early puberty seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions through the climate to genes.
Another riddle: Although boys have a hair of their faces and awe at a young age, the trend towards the full flowering of early puberty is not as obvious as it is for girls.
Other doctors attending the American Association of Children's Doctors (AAP) conference have added more complexities to the subject.
Acne and hairy are common even in infants and toddlers.
"We have to be careful when it comes to how we identify the actual onset of puberty," said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at the Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
