He said the new media tribunal "will always be biased because it is the extended hand of the government" and that restrictions on content and advertising would damage Kenya's position in the global economy.
"I hope the president will listen to us, and we will ask him to reject this bill and return it to MPs," he said.
According to the Star newspaper, the bill is effectively handing over "complete control over the media" to the government, and Standard reports that democracy and freedom of expression in Kenya have "worn a hard blow" and criticize the bill as "stricd."
Approval of the bill comes amid a series of measures aimed at strengthening national security immediately after the Islamic gunman attack in September at the Westgate shopping mall.
The authorities' anger was turned to the Kenyan media when they broadcast a security camera footage on which soldiers sent to the scene of the attack allegedly looted a luxury goods store.
The police chief responded by summoning two journalists and the media executive for questioning, but the summons was later withdrawn after media pressure.
Under the new bill, media companies can be fined up to 20 million by Kenyan shillings and individual journalists up to one million along with the risk of "official from the list" or they may be denied official journalistic accreditation.
The General Court also has the right to confiscate the property of the offender if the fine is not paid.
According to the Daily Nation, “even one fine is enough to eliminate most radio stations.”
It is also reported that these measures may have a liquidation impact on what is called the Kenyan “living blogosphere”.
Politicians know that if they silence the media, they can do whatever they want with impunity.
“You never know what might happen,” Nation journalist Mutuma Mathium wrote, describing Kenyan media as a key source of a system of mutual control and balancing in public life.
"If we leave it to the politicians, they will bring the country to bankruptcy and throw us back to hunting and collecting," he wrote.
Lawmakers in Kenya have been the target of criticism from the public in the past.
In May, they voted to lift cuts ordered by the National Pay Agency and to renew their fat salaries around 532 000 untaxed shillings per month, which thus rank among the highest in the world.
